title: Grateful Dead Live at Providence Civic Center on 1986-03-31
lineage: Cassette Master (Nakamichi CR-7A) > Tascam DA-3000 (DSF 1-bit/5.8 MHz) > KORG AudioGate 4 > FLAC; Edited & Mastered in Audacity by Joe Noel: Flac 24/96; Checksum & tags created in xACT; 24 bit to 16 bit with MusicConverter using sox-14-4-2
description:
Set 1

Mississippi Half Step-> Roadrunner-> West L.A. Fadeaway, My Brother Esau, Brown Eyed Women, Desolation Row-> Might As Well

Set 2

Feel Like A Stranger-> Ship of Fools-> Hand Jive-> Goin' Down The Road Feelin' Bad-> Drums-> Comes A Time-> Truckin'-> E: Johnny B. Goode

reviews.review_text: Good show/best recording despite the bad vibes It was a pretty contemplative show in a lot of ways, second set pre-drums in particular.  The Stranger was different, not a rave up like the typical first set opener but moodier and kind of spare and spacey as hell.  It's a second set to get lost in until the disruption.  There were a lot of locals that week and a lot of glow sticks flying around as well.  At first I thought it was a glow stick but that wouldn't make any sense unless Roger Clemens had thrown it.  I recall Bill K. waving his fist in the air in anger and I'm pretty sure the crowd reaction a minute or so later was when it looked like security might have caught the person.  The Truckin'>JBG are indeed rushed and that's it. Despite the bad vibes, it's a good Dead show from the tour.  Not up to the standards of earlier show but a unique setlist and good ensemble playing all around.  There were posters to sign the next day outside the venue and everyone assumed the two set openers were statements.  Bob's line the next night about being no such thing as April Fools made some of us wonder if they were still pissed at us (it had to have been about 80-90% of the same people both nights).
